# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chicken-scheme
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken's focus is quickly clear from its slogan: "*A practical and portable Scheme system*".
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken's main focus is the practical application of Scheme for writing real-world software.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Scheme is well known for its use in computer science curricula and programming language experimentation, but it has seen little use in business and industry.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken's community has produced a large set of libraries to perform a variety of tasks.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The Chicken wiki (the software running it is also a Chicken program) also contains a list of software that has been written in Chicken.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] By compiling to an intermediate representation, in this case portable C (as do Gambit and Bigloo), programs written in Chicken can be compiled for common popular operating systems such as Linux, macOS, other Unix-like systems, Windows, Haiku, and mobile platforms iOS and Android.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] It also has built-in support for cross-compiling programs and extensions, which allows it to be used on various embedded system platforms.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Like many Scheme compilers, Chicken uses standard C as an intermediate representation.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] A Scheme program is translated into C by the Chicken compiler, and then a C compiler translates the C program into machine code for the target computer architecture, producing an executable program.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The universal availability of C makes it useful for this purpose.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken's design was inspired by a 1994 paper by Henry Baker that outlined an innovative strategy to compile Scheme into C.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] A Scheme program is compiled into C functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] These C functions never reach the *return* statement; instead, they call a new continuation when complete.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] These continuations are C functions and are passed on as extra arguments to other C functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] So far, this is the essence of continuation-passing style.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Baker's novel idea is to use the C call stack for the Scheme heap.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Hence, normal C stack operations such as automatic variable creation, variable-sized array allocation, and so on can be used.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] When the stack fills up (that is, the stack pointer reaches the top of the stack), a garbage collection can be initiated.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The design used is a copying garbage collector originally devised by C.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Cheney, which copies all live continuations and other live objects to the heap.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Despite this, the C code does not copy C stack frames, only Scheme objects, so it does not require knowledge of the C implementation.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] In full, the Scheme heap consists of the C stack as the *nursery* together with the two heaps required by the generational garbage collector.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This approach gives the speed of the C stack for many operations, and it allows the use of continuations as simple calls to C functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Further, Baker's solution guarantees asymptotic tail recursive behavior, as required by the Scheme language standard.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The implementation in the Chicken Scheme compiler is even asymptotically *safe for space*.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken Scheme is mostly R5RS-compliant, with a few notable limitations and deviations.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] R7RS compatibility is supplied as an extension library.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The core system has basic support for UTF-8 characters, however the string indexing and manipulation procedures are not UTF-8 aware.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] An extension library exists which adds support for full UTF-8 awareness.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken has a large software repository of added libraries and programs, termed *eggs*.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This system is very similar to RubyGems.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Initially, these eggs were developed in one central svn repository, in which creating a tag would automatically cause a new version of the extension to become available for download.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Currently, eggs can be developed anywhere and under any version control system, while still maintaining *semi-automatic* release management when using most of the popular code hosting sites.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This release method is VCS-agnostic in the sense that the user does not need to have these VCSes installed.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The developer is free to host anywhere they choose, and can even choose to avoid public version control and distribute only plain tarballs.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] For all released eggs, the latest version is tested automatically as part of a continuous integration process.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] A canonical test server exists, where the core system and all eggs are tested daily against the most recent development version (to catch regressive bugs), and the most recent stable version (to ensure that everything works for users of the stable system).
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Also, anyone can volunteer to supply further testing capacity, on different: hardware, operating systems, or core releases.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken supports most of R5RS standard Scheme, but it also adds a few nonstandard features which are not available in all Scheme implementations.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Chicken compiling to C makes it possible to *inject* custom C code into the compiled result, which eases integrating with C libraries.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Its foreign function interface supports converting back and forth between most built-in C types and corresponding Scheme objects.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Also, extension libraries exist for interfacing to Python, Lua, and Java, via Java Native Interface (JNI) or a bridge.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] It is relatively easy to cross-compile Scheme code to another platform (for example for embedded use on a device).
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] To make cross-compiling possible for Scheme code, Chicken imposes a model of separate compiling: A compiled module consists of two shared libraries.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] One library contains the actual code which will be used at runtime (compiled for the target platform), and the other is an *import module*, which will be used to load the code which runs at compile-time (on the host platform), such as procedural macro code.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The Chicken compiler can also be easily cross-compiled.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] After translation to C has been achieved, one can simply use a C compiler which is set up to build for another platform.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Since version 4, Chicken has a built-in module system and support for low-level hygienic macros through *explicit renaming* macros (before version 4, this was available through an add-on library).
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Standard *syntax-rules* macros are also supported, and *implicit renaming* macros, which is basically a *reversed* version of explicit renaming.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This mechanism trades performance for convenience.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Each identifier not explicitly *injected* as unhygienic will be automatically renamed to avoid name capture.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The performance cost occurs because *implicit* renaming requires the macro-expander to retraverse the expressions two more times.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This cost is paid at expansion time, so a macro author must consider if longer compiling times are acceptable.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Since version 4.11, Chicken comes shipped with a debugger named *Feathers*.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] When Scheme code is compiled with the needed debugging option, *debugging events* are injected at specific points in the code.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] These are implemented as calls to a C function, which is relatively low-overhead when not actually debugging the code.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] When debugging, it will try to make a TCP connection to a Feathers server process, possibly on a different machine.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] The process is halted, the user may set breakpoints and start the program.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] Then, when the breakpoint is hit, the client (process being debugged) enters a command loop, which allows interrogation of the client, to read out variables, or mutate them.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This allows the compiler to catch variable type errors at compile-time, and perform type specialisation.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This specialisation makes it possible to remove several safety checks for type detection at runtime when the type can be deduced at compile-time.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This results in improved run-time performance.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] This *scrutinizer* does not allow cross-module flow analysis, so it can only be used to optimize code that's part of one compiling unit (or module).
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] CHICKEN Scheme was originally developed by Felix Winkelmann on Cygwin/gcc and later Visual C++ 5.0 on Windows 98.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] He came up with the name "CHICKEN" arbitrarily as the "first thing that came to my mind that day" thinking of a plastic toy of Feathers McGraw on his desk.
[src:chicken-scheme/chicken-scheme-implementation] As the project matured, he decided not to change the name out of superstition.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
