[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:chicken-scheme/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] In functional programming, **continuation-passing style** (**CPS**) is a style of programming in which control is passed explicitly in the form of a continuation.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This is contrasted with *direct style*, which is the usual style of programming.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Steele, Jr. coined the phrase in AI Memo 349 (1975), which sets out the first version of the Scheme programming language.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Reynolds gives a detailed account of the many discoveries of continuations.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] A function written in continuation-passing style takes an extra argument: an explicit *continuation*; i.e., a function of one argument.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] When the CPS function has computed its result value, it "returns" it by calling the continuation function with this value as the argument.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] That means that when invoking a CPS function, the calling function is required to supply a procedure to be invoked with the subroutine's "return" value.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Expressing code in this form makes a number of things explicit which are implicit in direct style.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Programs can be automatically transformed from direct style to CPS.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Compilers for functional and logic programming languages often use CPS as an intermediate representation where a compiler for an imperative or procedural programming language would use static single assignment form (SSA).
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] SSA is formally equivalent to a subset of CPS (excluding non-local control flow, which does not occur when CPS is used as intermediate representation).
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Functional compilers can also use A-normal form (ANF) (but only for languages requiring eager evaluation), rather than with *thunks* (described in the examples below) in CPS.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] CPS is used more frequently by compilers than by programmers as a local or global style.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] In CPS, each procedure takes an extra argument representing what should be done with the result the function is calculating.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This, along with a restrictive style prohibiting a variety of constructs usually available, is used to expose the semantics of programs, making them easier to analyze.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This style also makes it easy to express unusual control structures, like `catch/throw` or other non-local transfers of control.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] The key to CPS is to remember that (a) *every* function takes an extra argument known as its continuation, and (b) every argument in a function call must be either a variable or a lambda expression (not a more complex expression).
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This has the effect of turning expressions "inside-out" because the innermost parts of the expression must be evaluated first, thus CPS makes explicit the order of evaluation as well as the control flow.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Some examples of code in direct style and the corresponding CPS appear below.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] To call a procedure written in CPS from a procedure written in direct style, it is necessary to provide a continuation that will receive the result computed by the CPS procedure.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] In the example above (assuming that CPS primitives have been provided), we might call `(factorial& 10 (lambda (x) (display x) (newline)))`.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] There is some variety between compilers in the way primitive functions are provided in CPS.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Similarly, sometimes the `if` primitive is not included in CPS, and instead a function `if&` is provided which takes three arguments: a Boolean condition and the two thunks corresponding to the two arms of the conditional.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] The translations shown above show that CPS is a global transformation.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] The direct-style *factorial* takes, as might be expected, a single argument; the CPS *factorial&* takes two: the argument and a continuation.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Any function calling a CPS-ed function must either provide a new continuation or pass its own; any calls from a CPS-ed function to a non-CPS function will use implicit continuations.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Thus, to ensure the total absence of a function stack, the entire program must be in CPS.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] A function `pyth` to calculate a hypotenuse using the Pythagorean theorem can be written in Haskell.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] To transform the traditional function to CPS, its signature must be changed.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] First we calculate the square of *a* in `pyth'` function and pass a lambda function as a continuation which will accept a square of *a* as a first argument.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] And so on until the result of the calculations are reached.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] To get the result of this function we can pass `id` function as a final argument which returns the value that was passed to it unchanged: `pyth' 3 4 id == 5.0`.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] The mtl library, which is shipped with Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), has the module `Control.Monad.Cont`.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This module provides the Cont type, which implements Monad and some other useful functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Not only has the syntax become cleaner, but this type allows us to use a function `callCC` with type `MonadCont m => ((a -> m b) -> m a) -> m a`.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This function has one argument of a function type; that function argument accepts the function too, which discards all computations going after its call.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Programming with continuations can also be useful when a caller does not want to wait until the callee completes.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] For example, in user interface (UI) programming, a routine can set up dialog box fields and pass these, along with a continuation function, to the UI framework.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This call returns right away, allowing the application code to continue while the user interacts with the dialog box.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Once the user presses the "OK" button, the framework calls the continuation function with the updated fields.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Although this style of coding uses continuations, it is not full CPS.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] A similar idea can be used when the function must run in a different thread or on a different processor.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] The framework can execute the called function in a worker thread, then call the continuation function in the original thread with the worker's results.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Every call in CPS is a tail call, and the continuation is explicitly passed.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Using CPS without *tail call optimization* (TCO) will cause both the constructed continuation to potentially grow during recursion, and the call stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] This is usually undesirable, but has been used in interesting ways; see the Chicken Scheme compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] As CPS and TCO eliminate the concept of an implicit function return, their combined use can eliminate the need for a run-time stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Several compilers and interpreters for functional programming languages use this ability in novel ways.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Continuation passing style can be used to implement continuations and control flow operators in a functional language that does not feature first-class continuations but does have first-class functions and tail-call optimization.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Without tail-call optimization, techniques such as trampolining, i.e., using a loop that iteratively invokes thunk-returning functions, can be used; without first-class functions, it is even possible to convert tail calls into just gotos in such a loop.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Writing code in CPS, while not impossible, is often error-prone.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] There are various translations, usually defined as one- or two-pass conversions of pure lambda calculus, which convert direct style expressions into CPS expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Writing in trampolined style, however, is extremely difficult; when used, it is usually the target of some sort of transformation, such as compilation.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] A CPS transform is conceptually a Yoneda embedding.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] It is also similar to the embedding of lambda calculus in π-calculus.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Outside of computer science, CPS is of more general interest as an alternative to the conventional method of composing simple expressions into complex expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] For example, within linguistic semantics, Chris Barker and his collaborators have suggested that specifying the denotations of sentences using CPS might explain certain phenomena in natural language.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] In mathematics, the Curry–Howard isomorphism between computer programs and mathematical proofs relates continuation-passing style translation to a variation of double-negation embeddings of classical logic into intuitionistic (constructive) logic.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Unlike the regular double-negation translation, which maps atomic propositions *p* to ((*p* → ⊥) → ⊥), the continuation passing style replaces ⊥ by the type of the final expression.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Accordingly, the result is obtained by passing the identity function as a continuation to the CPS expression, as in the above example.
[src:chicken-scheme/continuation-passing-style] Classical logic itself relates to manipulating the continuation of programs directly, as in Scheme's call-with-current-continuation control operator, an observation due to Tim Griffin (using the closely related C control operator).
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:chicken-scheme/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In computer programming, an **S-expression** (or **symbolic expression**, abbreviated as **sexpr** or **sexp**) is an expression in a like-named notation for nested list (tree-structured) data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] S-expressions were invented for, and popularized by, the programming language Lisp, which uses them for source code as well as data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] *y*) where *x* and *y* are S-expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] This definition reflects LISP's representation of a list as a series of "cells", each one an ordered pair.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In plain lists, *y* points to the next cell (if any), thus forming a list.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The recursive clause of the definition means that both this representation and the S-expression notation can represent any binary tree.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] `NIL` is the special end-of-list object (alternatively written `()`, which is the only representation in Scheme).
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In the Lisp family of programming languages, S-expressions are used to represent both source code and data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Other uses of S-expressions are in Lisp-derived languages such as DSSSL, and as mark-up in communication protocols like IMAP and John McCarthy's CBCL.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It is also used as text representation of WebAssembly.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The details of the syntax and supported data types vary in the different languages, but the most common feature among these languages is the use of S-expressions and prefix notation.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] There are many variants of the S-expression format, supporting a variety of different syntaxes for different datatypes.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The character `#` is often used to prefix extensions to the syntax, e.g.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] `#x10` for hexadecimal integers, or `#\C` for characters.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] When representing source code in Lisp, the first element of an S-expression is commonly an operator or function name and any remaining elements are treated as arguments.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] This is called "prefix notation" or "Polish notation".
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] As an example, the Boolean expression written `4 == (2 + 2)` in C, is represented as `(= 4 (+ 2 2))` in Lisp's s-expr-based prefix notation.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] As noted above, the precise definition of "atom" varies across LISP-like languages.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] A quoted string can typically contain anything but a quote, while an unquoted identifier atom can typically contain anything but quotes, whitespace characters, parentheses, brackets, braces, backslashes, and semicolons.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In either case, a prohibited character can typically be included by escaping it with a preceding backslash.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The recursive case of the definition of S-expressions is traditionally implemented using cons cells.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] S-expressions were originally intended only for data to be manipulated by M-expressions, but the first implementation of Lisp was an interpreter of S-expression encodings of M-expressions, and Lisp programmers soon became accustomed to using S-expressions for both code and data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] This means that Lisp is homoiconic; that is, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Nested lists can be written as S-expressions: `((milk juice) (honey marmalade))` is a two-element S-expression whose elements are also two-element S-expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The whitespace-separated notation used in Lisp (and this article) is typical.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Line breaks (newline characters) usually qualify as separators.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Program code can be written in S-expressions, usually using prefix notation.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] S-expressions can be read in Lisp using the function READ.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] READ reads the textual representation of an S-expression and returns Lisp data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The function PRINT can be used to output an S-expression.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The output then can be read with the function READ, when all printed data objects have a readable representation.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Lisp has readable representations for numbers, strings, symbols, lists and many other data types.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Program code can be formatted as pretty printed S-expressions using the function PPRINT (note: with two Ps, short for *pretty*-print).
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Lisp programs are valid S-expressions, but not all S-expressions are valid Lisp programs.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] `(1.0 + 3.1)` is a valid S-expression, but not a valid Lisp program, since Lisp uses prefix notation and a floating point number (here 1.0) is not valid as an operation (the first element of the expression).
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] An S-expression preceded by a single quotation mark, as in `'x`, is syntactic sugar for a quoted S-expression, in this case `(quote x)`.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] S-expressions are also used for WebAssembly text format.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] S-expressions are often compared to XML: one key difference is that S-expressions have just one form of containment, the dotted pair, while XML tags can contain simple attributes, other tags, or CDATA, each using different syntax.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Another is that S-expressions do not define a reference mechanism, whereas XML provides a notion of unique identifiers and references to them.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] For simple use cases, S-expressions are simpler than XML, but for more advanced use cases, XML has a query language called XPath which many tools and third party libraries use to simplify the handling of XML data.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Standards for some Lisp-derived programming languages include a specification for their S-expression syntax.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] These include Common Lisp (ANSI standard document ANSI INCITS 226-1994 (R2004)), Scheme (R5RS and R6RS), and ISLISP.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In May 1997, Ron Rivest submitted an Internet Draft to be considered for publication as an RFC.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The draft defined a syntax based on Lisp S-expressions but intended for general-purpose data storage and exchange (similar to XML) rather than specifically for programming.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It was never approved as an RFC, but it has since been cited and used by other RFCs (e.g.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] RFC 2693) and several other publications.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It was originally intended for use in SPKI.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Rivest's format defines an S-expression as being either an octet-string (a series of bytes) or a finite list of other S-expressions.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It describes three interchange formats for expressing this structure.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] One is the "advanced transport", which is very flexible in terms of formatting, and is syntactically similar to Lisp-style expressions, but they are not identical.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] The advanced transport, for example, allows octet-strings to be represented verbatim (the string's length followed by a colon and the entire raw string), a quoted form allowing escape characters, hexadecimal, Base64, or placed directly as a "token" if it meets certain conditions.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Rivest's draft defines a canonical representation "for digital signature purposes".
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It is intended to be compact, easier to parse, and unique for any abstract S-expression.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] It only allows verbatim strings, and prohibits whitespace as formatting outside strings.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] This format has not been widely adapted for use outside of SPKI (some of the users being GnuPG, libgcrypt, Nettle, and GNU lsh).
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] Rivest's S-expressions web page provides C source code for a parser and generator (available under the MIT license), which could be adapted and embedded into other programs.
[src:chicken-scheme/s-expression] In addition, there are no restrictions on independently implementing the format.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme language is standardized in the official Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard and a *de facto* standard named the *Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme* (R*n*RS).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A widely implemented standard is R5RS (1998).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The most recently ratified standard of Scheme is "R7RS-small" (2013).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The more expansive and modular R6RS was ratified in 2007.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both trace their descent from R5RS; the timeline below reflects the chronological order of ratification.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme started in the 1970s as an attempt to understand Carl Hewitt's Actor model, for which purpose Steele and Sussman wrote a "tiny Lisp interpreter" using Maclisp and then "added mechanisms for creating actors and sending messages".
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme was originally called "Schemer", in the tradition of other Lisp-derived languages such as Planner or *Conniver*.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The current name resulted from the authors' use of the ITS operating system, which limited filenames to two components of at most six characters each.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently, "Schemer" is commonly used to refer to a Scheme programmer.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new language standardization process began at the 2003 Scheme workshop, with the goal of producing an R6RS standard in 2006.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This process broke with the earlier R*n*RS approach of unanimity.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS features a standard module system, allowing a split between the core language and libraries.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Several drafts of the R6RS specification were released, the final version being R5.97RS.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A successful vote resulted in ratifying the new standard, announced on August 28, 2007.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently the newest releases of various Scheme implementations support the R6RS standard.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is a portable reference implementation of the proposed implicitly phased libraries for R6RS, called psyntax, which loads and bootstraps itself properly on various older Scheme implementations.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A feature of R6RS is the record-type descriptor (RTD).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When an RTD is created and used, the record type representation can show the memory layout.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It also calculated object field bit mask and mutable Scheme object field bit masks, and helped the garbage collector know what to do with the fields without traversing the whole fields list that are saved in the RTD.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] RTD allows users to expand the basic RTD to create a new record system.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS introduces numerous significant changes to the language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The source code is now specified in Unicode, and a large subset of Unicode characters may now appear in Scheme symbols and identifiers, and there are other minor changes to the lexical rules.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Character data is also now specified in Unicode.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many standard procedures have been moved to the new standard libraries, which themselves form a large expansion of the standard, containing procedures and syntactic forms that were formerly not part of the standard.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new module system has been introduced, and systems for exception handling are now standardized.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Syntax-rules has been replaced with a more expressive syntactic abstraction facility (syntax-case) which allows the use of all of Scheme at macro expansion time.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Compliant implementations are now *required* to support Scheme's full numeric tower, and the semantics of numbers have been expanded, mainly in the direction of support for the IEEE 754 standard for floating point numerical representation.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard has caused controversy because some see it as a departure from the minimalist philosophy.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Two working groups were created to work on these two new versions of Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme Reports Process site has links to the working groups' charters, public discussions and issue tracking system.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The ninth draft of R7RS (small language) was made available on April 15, 2013.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A vote ratifying this draft closed on May 20, 2013, and the final report has been available since August 6, 2013, describing "the 'small' language of that effort: therefore it cannot be considered in isolation as the successor to R6RS".
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is primarily a functional programming language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It shares many characteristics with other members of the Lisp programming language family.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's very simple syntax is based on s-expressions, parenthesized lists in which a prefix operator is followed by its arguments.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs thus consist of sequences of nested lists.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lists are also the main data structure in Scheme, leading to a close equivalence between source code and data formats (homoiconicity).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs can easily create and evaluate pieces of Scheme code dynamically.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reliance on lists as data structures is shared by all Lisp dialects.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits a rich set of list-processing primitives such as `cons`, `car` and `cdr` from its Lisp progenitors.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme uses strictly but dynamically typed variables and supports first class procedures.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus, procedures can be assigned as values to variables or passed as arguments to procedures.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This section concentrates mainly on innovative features of the language, including those features that distinguish Scheme from other Lisps.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Unless stated otherwise, descriptions of features relate to the R5RS standard.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In examples provided in this section, the notation "===> result" is used to indicate the result of evaluating the expression on the immediately preceding line.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is the same convention used in R5RS.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is a very simple language, much easier to implement than many other languages of comparable expressive power.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This ease is attributable to the use of lambda calculus to derive much of the syntax of the language from more primitive forms.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For instance of the 23 s-expression-based syntactic constructs defined in the R5RS Scheme standard, 14 are classed as derived or library forms, which can be written as macros involving more fundamental forms, principally lambda.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] : define, lambda, quote, if, define-syntax, let-syntax, letrec-syntax, syntax-rules, set!
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example: a macro to implement `let` as an expression using `lambda` to perform the variable bindings.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus using `let` as defined above a Scheme implementation would rewrite "`(let ((a 1)(b 2)) (+ b a))`" as "`((lambda (a b) (+ b a)) 1 2)`", which reduces implementation's task to that of coding procedure instantiations.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In 1998, Sussman and Steele remarked that the minimalism of Scheme was not a conscious design goal, but rather the unintended outcome of the design process.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like most modern programming languages and unlike earlier Lisps such as Maclisp, Scheme is lexically scoped: all possible variable bindings in a program unit can be analyzed by reading the text of the program unit without considering the contexts in which it may be called.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This contrasts with dynamic scoping which was characteristic of early Lisp dialects, because of the processing costs associated with the primitive textual substitution methods used to implement lexical scoping algorithms in compilers and interpreters of the day.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In those Lisps, it was fully possible for a reference to a free variable inside a procedure to refer to quite distinct bindings external to the procedure, depending on the context of the call.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The impetus to incorporate lexical scoping, which was an unusual scoping model in the early 1970s, into their new version of Lisp, came from Sussman's studies of ALGOL.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] He suggested that ALGOL-like lexical scoping mechanisms would help to realize their initial goal of implementing Carl Hewitt's Actor model in Lisp.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alonzo Church's mathematical notation, the lambda calculus, has inspired Lisp's use of "lambda" as a keyword for introducing a procedure, as well as influencing the development of functional programming techniques involving the use of higher-order functions in Lisp.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] But early Lisps were not suitable expressions of the lambda calculus because of their treatment of free variables.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A formal lambda system has axioms and a complete calculation rule.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It is helpful for the analysis using mathematical logic and tools.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In this system, calculation can be seen as a directional deduction.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The syntax of lambda calculus follows the recursive expressions from x, y, z, ...,parentheses, spaces, the period and the symbol λ.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The function of lambda calculation includes: First, serve as a starting point of powerful mathematical logic.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Second, it can reduce the requirement of programmers to consider the implementation details, because it can be used to imitate machine evaluation.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Finally, the lambda calculation created a substantial meta-theory.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introduction of lexical scope resolved the problem by making an equivalence between some forms of lambda notation and their practical expression in a working programming language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They introduced continuation-passing style along with their first description of Scheme in the first of the Lambda Papers, and in subsequent papers, they proceeded to demonstrate the raw power of this practical use of lambda calculus.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits its block structure from earlier block structured languages, particularly ALGOL.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, blocks are implemented by three *binding constructs*: `let`, `let*` and `letrec`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Blocks can be nested to create arbitrarily complex block structures according to the need of the programmer.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The use of block structuring to create local bindings alleviates the risk of namespace collision that can otherwise occur.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The other variant, `letrec`, is designed to enable mutually recursive procedures to be bound to one another.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] All procedures bound in a single `letrec` may refer to one another by name, as well as to values of variables defined earlier in the same `letrec`, but they may not refer to *values* defined later in the same `letrec`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A variant of `let`, the "named let" form, has an identifier after the `let` keyword.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This binds the let variables to the argument of a procedure whose name is the given identifier and whose body is the body of the let form.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The body may be repeated as desired by calling the procedure.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The named let is widely used to implement iteration.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like any procedure in Scheme, the procedure created in the named let is a first-class object.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme has an iteration construct, `do`, but it is more idiomatic in Scheme to use tail recursion to express iteration.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Standard-conforming Scheme implementations are required to optimize tail calls so as to support an unbounded number of active tail calls (R5RS sec.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 3.5)—a property the Scheme report describes as *proper tail recursion*—making it safe for Scheme programmers to write iterative algorithms using recursive structures, which are sometimes more intuitive.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Tail recursive procedures and the *named `let`* form provide support for iteration using tail recursion.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations in Scheme are first-class objects.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme provides the procedure `call-with-current-continuation` (also known as `call/cc`) to capture the current continuation by packing it up as an escape procedure bound to a formal argument in a procedure provided by the programmer.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.4) First-class continuations enable the programmer to create non-local control constructs such as iterators, coroutines, and backtracking.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations can be used to emulate the behavior of return statements in imperative programming languages.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following function `find-first`, given function `func` and list `lst`, returns the first element `x` in `lst` such that `(func x)` returns true.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following example, a traditional programmer's puzzle, shows that Scheme can handle continuations as first-class objects, binding them to variables and passing them as arguments to procedures.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast to Common Lisp, all data and procedures in Scheme share a common namespace, whereas in Common Lisp functions and data have separate namespaces making it possible for a function and a variable to have the same name, and requiring special notation for referring to a function as a value.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is sometimes known as the "Lisp-1 vs.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lisp-2" distinction, referring to the unified namespace of Scheme and the separate namespaces of Common Lisp.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, the same primitives that are used to manipulate and bind data can be used to bind procedures.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is no equivalent of Common Lisp's `defun` and `#'` primitives.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This subsection documents design decisions that have been taken over the years which have given Scheme a particular character, but are not the direct outcomes of the original design.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme specifies a comparatively full set of numerical datatypes including complex and rational types, which is known in Scheme as the numerical tower (R5RS sec.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard treats these as abstractions, and does not commit the implementor to any particular internal representations.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Numbers may have the quality of exactness.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] An exact number can only be produced by a sequence of exact operations involving other exact numbers—inexactness is thus contagious.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard specifies that any two implementations must produce equivalent results for all operations resulting in exact numbers.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard specifies procedures `exact->inexact` and `inexact->exact` which can be used to change the exactness of a number.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `inexact->exact` produces "the exact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `exact->inexact` produces "the inexact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard omits these procedures from the main report, but specifies them as R5RS compatibility procedures in the standard library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard, Scheme implementations are not required to implement the whole numerical tower, but they must implement "a coherent subset consistent with both the purposes of the implementation and the spirit of the Scheme language" (R5RS sec.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The new R6RS standard does require implementation of the whole tower, and "exact integer objects and exact rational number objects of practically unlimited size and precision, and to implement certain procedures...so they always return exact results when given exact arguments" (R6RS sec.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 1: exact arithmetic in an implementation that supports exact rational complex numbers.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 2: Same arithmetic in an implementation that supports neither exact rational numbers nor complex numbers but does accept real numbers in rational notation.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both implementations conform to the R5RS standard but the second does not conform to R6RS because it does not implement the full numerical tower.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme supports delayed evaluation through the `delay` form and the procedure `force`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The lexical context of the original definition of the promise is preserved, and its value is also preserved after the first use of `force`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The promise is only ever evaluated once.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These primitives, which produce or handle values known as promises, can be used to implement advanced lazy evaluation constructs such as streams.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R6RS standard, these are no longer primitives, but instead, are provided as part of the R5RS compatibility library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R5RS, a suggested implementation of `delay` and `force` is given, implementing the promise as a procedure with no arguments (a thunk) and using memoization to ensure that it is only ever evaluated once, irrespective of the number of times `force` is called (R5RS sec.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] SRFI 41 enables the expression of both finite and infinite sequences with extraordinary economy.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Lisps specify an order of evaluation for procedure arguments.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] ev is a procedure that describes the argument passed to it, then returns the value of the argument.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast with other Lisps, the appearance of an expression in the operator position (the first item) of a Scheme expression is quite legal, as long as the result of the expression in the operator position is a procedure.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In calling the procedure "+" to add 1 and 2, the expressions (ev +), (ev 1) and (ev 2) may be evaluated in any order, as long as the effect is not as if they were evaluated in parallel.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus the following three lines may be displayed in any order by standard Scheme when the above example code is executed, although the text of one line may not be interleaved with another because that would violate the sequential evaluation constraint.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard and in later reports, the syntax of Scheme can easily be extended via the macro system.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard introduced a powerful hygienic macro system that allows the programmer to add new syntactic constructs to the language using a simple pattern matching sublanguage (R5RS sec 4.3).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to this, the hygienic macro system had been relegated to an appendix of the R4RS standard, as a "high level" system alongside a "low level" macro system, both of which were treated as extensions to Scheme rather than an essential part of the language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of the hygienic macro system, also called `syntax-rules`, are required to respect the lexical scoping of the rest of the language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is assured by special naming and scoping rules for macro expansion and avoids common programming errors that can occur in the macro systems of other programming languages.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS specifies a more sophisticated transformation system, `syntax-case`, which has been available as a language extension to R5RS Scheme for some time.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Invocations of macros and procedures bear a close resemblance—both are s-expressions—but they are treated differently.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When the compiler encounters an s-expression in the program, it first checks to see if the symbol is defined as a syntactic keyword within the current lexical scope.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If so, it then attempts to expand the macro, treating the items in the tail of the s-expression as arguments without compiling code to evaluate them, and this process is repeated recursively until no macro invocations remain.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is not a syntactic keyword, the compiler compiles code to evaluate the arguments in the tail of the s-expression and then to evaluate the variable represented by the symbol at the head of the s-expression and call it as a procedure with the evaluated tail expressions passed as arguments to it.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Scheme implementations also provide additional macro systems.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Among popular ones are syntactic closures, explicit renaming macros and `define-macro`, a non-hygienic macro system similar to `defmacro` system provided in Common Lisp.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The inability to specify whether or not a macro is hygienic is one of the shortcomings of the macro system.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alternative models for expansion such as scope sets provide a potential solution.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to R5RS, Scheme had no standard equivalent of the `eval` procedure which is ubiquitous in other Lisps, although the first Lambda Paper had described `evaluate` as "similar to the LISP function EVAL" and the first Revised Report in 1978 replaced this with `enclose`, which took two arguments.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The second, third and fourth revised reports omitted any equivalent of `eval`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reason for this confusion is that in Scheme with its lexical scoping the result of evaluating an expression depends on where it is evaluated.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the outer environment, where `name` is defined, the result is the sum of the operands.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the inner environment, where the symbol "+" has been bound to the value of the procedure "*", the result is the product of the two operands.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS resolves this confusion by specifying three procedures that return environments and providing a procedure `eval` that takes an s-expression and an environment and evaluates the expression in the environment provided.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.5) R6RS extends this by providing a procedure called `environment` by which the programmer can specify exactly which objects to import into the evaluation environment.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `interaction-environment` is the interpreter's global environment.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In most dialects of Lisp including Common Lisp, by convention the value `NIL` evaluates to the value false in a Boolean expression.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, since the IEEE standard in 1991, all values except `#f`, including `NIL`'s equivalent in Scheme which is written as `'()`, evaluate to the value true in a Boolean expression.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Where the constant representing the Boolean value of true is `T` in most Lisps, in Scheme it is `#t`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme the primitive datatypes are disjoint.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Only one of the following predicates can be true of any Scheme object: `boolean?`, `pair?`, `symbol?`, `number?`, `char?`, `string?`, `vector?`, `port?`, `procedure?`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Within the numerical datatype, by contrast, the numerical values overlap.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, an integer value satisfies all of the `integer?`, `rational?`, `real?`, `complex?` and `number?` predicates at the same time.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Type dependent equivalence operations also exist in Scheme: `string=?` and `string-ci=?` compare two strings (the latter performs a case-independent comparison); `char=?` and `char-ci=?` compare characters; `=` compares numbers.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Up to the R5RS standard, the standard comment in Scheme was a semicolon, which makes the rest of the line invisible to Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's input and output is based on the *port* datatype.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R5RS sec 6.6) R5RS defines two default ports, accessible with the procedures `current-input-port` and `current-output-port`, which correspond to the Unix notions of standard input and standard output.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations also provide `current-error-port`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Redirection of input and standard output is supported in the standard, by standard procedures such as `with-input-from-file` and `with-output-to-file`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations provide string ports with similar redirection capabilities, enabling many normal input-output operations to be performed on string buffers instead of files, using procedures described in SRFI 6.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies much more sophisticated and capable port procedures and many new types of port.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following examples are written in strict R5RS Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 5: As 2, but with using call-with-output-file to send output to a file.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Similar procedures are provided for input.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS Scheme provides the predicates `input-port?` and `output-port?`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For character input and output, `write-char`, `read-char`, `peek-char` and `char-ready?` are provided.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For writing and reading Scheme expressions, Scheme provides `read` and `write`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] On a read operation, the result returned is the end-of-file object if the input port has reached the end of the file, and this can be tested using the predicate `eof-object?`.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] With the standard, SRFI 28 also defines a basic formatting procedure resembling Common Lisp's `format` function, after which it is named.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, procedures are bound to variables.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] At R5RS the language standard formally mandated that programs may change the variable bindings of built-in procedures, effectively redefining them.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS every binding, including the standard ones, belongs to some library, and all exported bindings are immutable.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R6RS sec 7.1) Because of this, redefinition of standard procedures by mutation is forbidden.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Instead, it is possible to import a different procedure under the name of a standard one, which in effect is similar to redefinition.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Standard Scheme, procedures that convert from one datatype to another contain the character string "->" in their name, predicates end with a "?", and procedures that change the value of already-allocated data end with a "!".
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These conventions are often followed by Scheme programmers.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In formal contexts such as Scheme standards, the word "procedure" is used in preference to "function" to refer to a lambda expression or primitive procedure.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In normal usage, the words "procedure" and "function" are used interchangeably.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Procedure application is sometimes referred to formally as *combination*.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] As in other Lisps, the term "thunk" is used in Scheme to refer to a procedure with no arguments.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The term "proper tail recursion" refers to the property of all Scheme implementations, that they perform tail-call optimization so as to support an indefinite number of active tail calls.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The language is formally defined in the standards R5RS (1998), R6RS (2007), and R7RS (2013).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They describe standard "forms": keywords and accompanying syntax, which provide the control structure of the language, and standard procedures which perform common tasks.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This table describes the standard forms in Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some forms appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Forms marked "L" in this table are classed as derived "library" forms in the standard and are often implemented as macros using more fundamental forms in practice, making the task of implementation much easier than in other languages.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] While `begin` is defined as a library syntax in R5RS, the expander must know about it to achieve the splicing function.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS it is no longer a library syntax.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following two tables describe the standard procedures in R5RS Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS is far more extensive and a summary of this type would not be practical.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some procedures appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] String and character procedures that contain "-ci" in their names perform case-independent comparisons between their arguments: upper case and lower case versions of the same character are taken to be equal.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of - and / that take more than two arguments are defined but left optional at R5RS.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Because of Scheme's minimalism, many common procedures and syntactic forms are not defined by the standard.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In order to keep the core language small but facilitate standardization of extensions, the Scheme community has a "Scheme Request for Implementation" (SRFI) process by which extension libraries are defined through careful discussion of extension proposals.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many of the SRFIs are supported by all or most Scheme implementations.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The elegant, minimalist design has made Scheme a popular target for language designers, hobbyists, and educators, and because of its small size, that of a typical interpreter, it is also a popular choice for embedded systems and scripting.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies a much broader language, in an attempt to broaden its appeal to programmers.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Almost all implementations provide a traditional Lisp-style read–eval–print loop for development and debugging.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many also compile Scheme programs to executable binary.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Support for embedding Scheme code in programs written in other languages is also common, as the relative simplicity of Scheme implementations makes it a popular choice for adding scripting capabilities to larger systems developed in languages such as C.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Gambit, Chicken, and Bigloo Scheme interpreters compile Scheme to C, which makes embedding far easier.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Further, Bigloo's compiler can be configured to generate bytecode for the Java virtual machine (JVM), and has an experimental bytecode generator for .NET.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some implementations support added features.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, Kawa and JScheme provide integration with Java classes, and the Scheme to C compilers often make it easy to use external libraries written in C, up to allowing the embedding of C code in the Scheme source code.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Another example is Pvts, which offers a set of visual tools that support Scheme learning.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is widely used by several schools; in particular, several introductory computer science courses use Scheme in conjunction with the textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* (SICP).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For the past 12 years, PLT has run the ProgramByDesign (formerly TeachScheme!) project, which has exposed close to 600 high school teachers and thousands of high school students to rudimentary Scheme programming.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] MIT's old introductory programming class 6.001 was taught in Scheme, Although 6.001 has been replaced by more modern courses, SICP continues to be taught at MIT.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Likewise, the introductory class at UC Berkeley, CS 61A, was until 2011 taught entirely in Scheme, save minor diversions into Logo to demonstrate dynamic scope.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Today, like MIT, Berkeley has replaced the syllabus with a more modern version that is primarily taught in Python 3, but the current syllabus is still based on the old curriculum, and parts of the class are still taught in Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The textbook *How to Design Programs* is used by some institutes of higher education for their introductory computer science courses.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Worcester Polytechnic Institute uses Scheme exclusively for its introductory course Introduction to Program Design (CS1101).
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology uses Scheme in its more advanced Programming Language Concepts course.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Brandeis University's core course, Structure and Interpretations of Computer Programs (COSI121b), is also taught exclusively in Scheme by theoretical computer scientist Harry Mairson.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Indiana University's introductory class, C211, is taught entirely in Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A self-paced version of the course, CS 61AS, continues to use Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introductory computer science courses at Yale and Grinnell College are also taught in Scheme.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In computer science, a **tail call** is a subroutine call performed as the final action of a procedure.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] If the target of a tail is the same subroutine, the subroutine is said to be **tail recursive**, which is a special case of direct recursion.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] **Tail recursion** (or **tail-end recursion**) is particularly useful, and is often easy to optimize in implementations.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail calls can be implemented without adding a new stack frame to the call stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Most of the frame of the current procedure is no longer needed, and can be replaced by the frame of the tail call, modified as appropriate (similar to overlay for processes, but for function calls).
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The program can then jump to the called subroutine.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Producing such code instead of a standard call sequence is called **tail-call elimination** or **tail-call optimization**.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination allows procedure calls in tail position to be implemented as efficiently as goto statements, thus allowing efficient structured programming.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Not all programming languages require tail-call elimination.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] However, in functional programming languages, tail-call elimination is often guaranteed by the language standard, allowing tail recursion to use a similar amount of memory as an equivalent loop.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The special case of tail-recursive calls, when a function calls itself, may be more amenable to call elimination than general tail calls.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] When the language semantics do not explicitly support general tail calls, a compiler can often still optimize **sibling calls**, or tail calls to functions which take and return the same types as the caller.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] When a function is called, the computer must "remember" the place it was called from, the *return address*, so that it can return to that location with the result once the call is complete.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Typically, this information is saved on the call stack, a list of return locations in the order that the call locations were reached.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In addition, compilers allocate memory for local variables of the called function and push register content (if any and/or relevant) onto the stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Typically, it is done by allocating a stack frame including saved registers, space allocated for non-register local variables, return address and call parameters (unless they are passed in registers).
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This, however, leads to complete loss of the caller's stack frame, which is sometimes considered as a hindrance in debugging.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The tail call doesn't have to appear lexically after all other statements in the source code; it is only important that the calling function return immediately after the tail call, returning the tail call's result if any, since the calling function is bypassed when the optimization is performed.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For non-recursive function calls, this is usually an optimization that saves only a little time and space, since there are not that many different functions available to call.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] When dealing with recursive or mutually recursive functions where recursion happens through tail calls, however, the stack space and the number of returns saved can grow to be very significant, since a function can call itself, directly or indirectly, creating a new call stack frame each time.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination often reduces asymptotic stack space requirements from linear, or O(n), to constant, or O(1).
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination is thus required by the standard definitions of some programming languages, such as Scheme, and languages in the ML family among others.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The Scheme language definition formalizes the intuitive notion of tail position exactly, by specifying which syntactic forms allow having results in tail context.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Implementations allowing an unlimited number of tail calls to be active at the same moment, thanks to tail-call elimination, can also be called 'properly tail recursive'.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Besides space and execution efficiency, tail-call elimination is important in the functional programming idiom known as continuation-passing style (CPS), which would otherwise quickly run out of stack space.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] A tail call can be located just before the syntactical end of a function.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Here, both `a(data)` and `b(data)` are calls, but `b` is the last thing the procedure executes before returning and is thus in tail position.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Here, both calls to `b` and `c` are in tail position.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This is because each of them lies in the end of if-branch respectively, even though the first one is not syntactically at the end of `bar`'s body.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The call to `a(data)` is in tail position in `foo2`, but it is **not** in tail position either in `foo1` or in `foo3`, because control must return to the caller to allow it to inspect or modify the return value before returning it.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This is not written in a tail-recursive style, because the multiplication function ("*") is in the tail position.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This program assumes applicative-order evaluation.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The inner procedure `fact-iter` calls itself *last* in the control flow.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This reorganization saves space because no state except for the calling function's address needs to be saved, either on the stack or on the heap, and the call stack frame for `fact-iter` is reused for the intermediate results storage.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This also means that the programmer need not worry about running out of stack or heap space for extremely deep recursions.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In typical implementations, the tail-recursive variant will be substantially faster than the other variant, but only by a constant factor.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Some programmers working in functional languages will rewrite recursive code to be tail recursive so they can take advantage of this feature.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This often requires addition of an "accumulator" argument (`product` in the above example) to the function.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Thus in tail-recursive translation such a call is transformed into first creating a new list node and setting its `first` field, and *then* making the tail call with the pointer to the node's `rest` field as argument, to be filled recursively.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The same effect is achieved when the recursion is *guarded* under a lazily evaluated data constructor, which is automatically achieved in lazy programming languages like Haskell.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In this form the function is not tail recursive, because control returns to the caller after the recursive call duplicates the rest of the input list.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Even if it were to allocate the *head* node before duplicating the rest, it would still need to plug in the result of the recursive call into the `next` field *after* the call.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] So the function is *almost* tail recursive.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Warren's method pushes the responsibility of filling the `next` field into the recursive call itself, which thus becomes tail call.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The callee now appends to the end of the growing list, rather than have the caller prepend to the beginning of the returned list.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The work is now done on the way *forward* from the list's start, *before* the recursive call which then proceeds further, instead of *backward* from the list's end, *after* the recursive call has returned its result.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] It is thus similar to the accumulating parameter technique, turning a recursive computation into an iterative one.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Characteristically for this technique, a parent frame is created on the execution call stack, which the tail-recursive callee can reuse as its own call frame if the tail-call optimization is present.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In a paper delivered to the ACM conference in Seattle in 1977, Guy L.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Steele summarized the debate over the GOTO and structured programming, and observed that procedure calls in the tail position of a procedure can be best treated as a direct transfer of control to the called procedure, typically eliminating unnecessary stack manipulation operations.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Since such "tail calls" are very common in Lisp, a language where procedure calls are ubiquitous, this form of optimization considerably reduces the cost of a procedure call compared to other implementations.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Steele argued that poorly-implemented procedure calls had led to an artificial perception that the GOTO was cheap compared to the procedure call.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Steele cited evidence that well-optimized numerical algorithms in Lisp could execute faster than code produced by then-available commercial Fortran compilers because the cost of a procedure call in Lisp was much lower.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In Scheme, a Lisp dialect developed by Steele with Gerald Jay Sussman, tail-call elimination is guaranteed to be implemented in any interpreter.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail recursion is important to some high-level languages, especially functional and logic languages and members of the Lisp family.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In these languages, tail recursion is the most commonly used way (and sometimes the only way available) of implementing iteration.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The language specification of Scheme requires that tail calls are to be optimized so as not to grow the stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For these cases, optimizing tail recursion remains trivial, but general tail-call optimization may be harder to implement efficiently.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For example, in the Java virtual machine (JVM), tail-recursive calls can be eliminated (as this reuses the existing call stack), but general tail calls cannot be (as this changes the call stack).
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] As a result, functional languages such as Scala that target the JVM can efficiently implement direct tail recursion, but not mutual tail recursion.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The GCC, LLVM/Clang, and Intel compiler suites perform tail-call optimization for C and other languages at higher optimization levels or when the `-foptimize-sibling-calls` option is passed.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Various implementation methods are available.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Tail calls are often optimized by interpreters and compilers of functional programming and logic programming languages to more efficient forms of iteration.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For example, Scheme programmers commonly express while loops as calls to procedures in tail position and rely on the Scheme compiler or interpreter to substitute the tail calls with more efficient jump instructions.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For compilers generating assembly directly, tail-call elimination is easy: it suffices to replace a call opcode with a jump one, after fixing parameters on the stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] After subroutine `A` completes, it will then return directly to the return address of `foo`, omitting the unnecessary `ret` statement.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Typically, the subroutines being called need to be supplied with parameters.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] The generated code thus needs to make sure that the call frame for A is properly set up before jumping to the tail-called subroutine.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] For instance, on platforms where the call stack does not just contain the return address, but also the parameters for the subroutine, the compiler may need to emit instructions to adjust the call stack.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This code is more efficient both in terms of execution speed and use of stack space.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] From a compiler's perspective, a pure tail call is most visible in recursive functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] A tail-call optimizer recognizes that the current stack frame is no longer needed after the call.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This optimized code is physically identical to an imperative `while` loop, executing with strictly bounded memory and maximal speed.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] In bare-metal environments and formal automata theory, a pure tail call is defined primarily by its space complexity: **a pure tail call occurs when the stack space is strictly bounded during recursion**.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] By guaranteeing that the stack pointer does not grow proportionally to the recursion depth, tail calls allow infinitely deep recursive evaluation to operate within strict physical memory constraints (such as a microkernel or a boot sector).
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This physically transforms the call stack into a bounded state machine.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] A tail call without recursion is physically equivalent to an assembly `JMP` instruction.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This property makes the tail call a fundamental primitive for implementing high-performance coroutines.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] By replacing the traditional `CALL` and `RET` cycle with a direct jump to the next state, an execution engine can "hand off" control between different functional units in constant stack space.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This mechanism is central to Continuation-passing style, where the program never returns, but instead performs a sequence of tail calls to transition between cooperative states.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Since many Scheme compilers use C as an intermediate target code, the tail recursion must be encoded in C without growing the stack, even if the C compiler does not optimize tail calls.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Many implementations achieve this by using a device known as a trampoline, a piece of code that repeatedly calls functions.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] All functions are entered via the trampoline.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] This ensures that the C stack does not grow and iteration can continue indefinitely.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] It is possible to implement trampolines using higher-order functions in languages that support them, such as Groovy, Visual Basic .NET and C#.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] When the stack reaches its maximum permitted size, objects on the stack are garbage-collected using the Cheney algorithm by moving all live data into a separate heap.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Following this, the stack is unwound ("popped") and the program resumes from the state saved just before the garbage collection.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] Baker says "Appel's method avoids making a large number of small trampoline bounces by occasionally jumping off the Empire State Building." The garbage collection ensures that mutual tail recursion can continue indefinitely.
[src:chicken-scheme/tail-call] However, this approach requires that no C function call ever returns, since there is no guarantee that its caller's stack frame still exists; therefore, it involves a much more dramatic internal rewriting of the program code: continuation-passing style.
